    "summary": "I'm a research engineer who is passionate about implementing novel medical imaging techniques in clinical applications. I have experience in medical image acquisition, reconstruction, post-processing and machine learning and an affinity with curating medical biomarkers and using machine learning tools for regression and classification.\n\nMy post-doctoral research focuses on using multi-modal MRI techniques for differentially diagnosing movement disorders, using iron-sensitive MRI, neuromelanin MRI, morphological features on T1-weighted images and diffusion-weighted MRI for assessing white-matter integrity in the brain. \n\nI'm a principal investigator on a clinical study investigating the benefit of quantitative MRI for diagnosing parkinsonisms. This project is funded by a personal grant from Parkinson NL.\n\nI like to deliver results beyond academic papers, with code and tools made publicly available.\n\nMy PhD in was MRI physics, focused on rapid MR image acquisition using Simultaneous Multi-Slice MRI. This Accelerated MRI by acquiring data from multiple slices. I designed tailored waveforms using digital filter design and constrained optimization which incorporate physical hardware limitations. This way, novel imaging techniques can be used without the need to upgrade hardware, using merely a 'software'-solution.\n\nI trained as an electrical and electronic engineer at Imperial College London, with emphasis on signal processing and digital filtering.",
