                    "description": "PhD project in MRI physics involves developing new imaging methods to reduce MRI scan duration.\nThe motivation for this is that MRI systems are expensive to acquire and maintain, and so MRI can be made more cost-effective by increasing patient throughput. Shorter scans can also reduce image artefacts due to body motion either caused by breathing or patient motion.\n\nThe technique I work on to accelerate MRI acquisition is known as multiband imaging, which accelerates the acquisition of volumetric MRI data by acquiring multiple slices simultaneously.\n\nAn essential part of this imaging methods is to transmit multiband radio-frequency (RF) pulses, which are short pulses transmitted from RF antennas within the MRI system into the patients body. Multiband RF pulses are special because they act on multiple slices simultaneously.\n\nThe more slices the better as it relates to the acceleration of your scan time. However high acceleration leads to either:\n1) Pulses which are too long in duration, take too long to transmit and lead to signal loss.\n2) Pulses with require too much power, which cannot be transmitted using modern hardware. \n\nFinding the perfect balance between these two is main topic of my PhD.",
